topics.body:
"@ArcticEight":/dis/the-time-wasting-thread/post/54b8b00063687215e0850300#post_54b8b00063687215e0850300
It would drastically reduce the cost of a lot of things.  Basically imagine a 2000 square foot house 100% complete with wiring, insulation and everything for only $5000 brand new.  It's going to change the world so much that companies are both terrified and excited.  Imagine cars costing a quarter of their current price or electronics for much cheaper.

The reason why it has people terrified is because what might happen is a rapid devaluing of houses with everyone wanting to get 3d printed houses because of their cheap price might cause another housing crash.  It could eliminate tens of millions of jobs.


Upside:
Exponentially cheaper products.
Extremely cheaper houses mean more home owners.
Much cheaper electronics means more people having access to the internet.
Much cheaper goods means people buying those goods.
Downside:
Potentially catastrophic deflation of money.
Cheaper houses means home values of existing homes goes down; there could be entire ghost cities where people just left their old houses and buildings to rot.
3D printing electronics means tens of millions of people out of jobs.
Massive deflation means we'll never pay off the deficit ever.
